result.execSummary:
The defendant Jody L Bungert was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess/Illegally Obtained Prescription, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 450.11(7)(h).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Costs to be paid directly to the Waushara County Clerk of Court within 60 days or establish a payment plan.  Failure to pay may result in suspension of your driver's license, tax intercept, a civil judgment being entered against you, a warrant being issued for your arrest for contempt and/or the debt being turned over to a collection agency.

Defendant is entitled to Good Time Credit and Huber Privileges. The court has no objection to the sentence being served in another jurisdiction.
Consecutive to: Any existing sentence currently being served.

records.addlTxt: of Bail/Bond Hearing 2/25/15, Initial Appearance 3/9/2015, Sentencing Hearing 5/8/2015 & Motion Hearing 6/19/2015
To Appellate Attorney with copy of case file
of Plea Hearing - April 22, 2015

Case Called @ 02:25 PM: Defendant Jody L Bungert in court with attorney William Lennon.  Steven Paul Anderson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court convenes today in response to new factors presented in the toxicology report.  No contest made to factual validity of the conduct involved, rather the substance involved is a valid RX held by Def.  Argument by Atty Lennon.  Argument by ADA - State was not aware that there was a valid RX for the substance - admits confusion over the substance that factored into the amendment.  Further argument by Atty Lennon.  Police Officer reports provided for Court's review as to the substance in question.  Highlighting for the Court the substance on the toxicology report.  Def confirms for the Court that she is not contesting the plea as entered - admits contraband introduced into the Jail setting and is not requesting to withdraw the plea.  Confirms valid RX for the substance in the toxicology report.  Court finds a new factor exists to evaluate sentencing.  Controlled substance with valid RX.  Finds Def is entitled to resentencing.  No statement offered.   Court reminds Def of the gravity of the conduct involved.  All conditions of sentence previously directed are reimposed - specifically imposition of a sentence of 30 days WCJ rather than 60 consecutive to any existing sentence currently being served - Commence 7/1/15.    Sentence adjusted accordingly.  Huber and GT credit.  Atty Lennon states that Notice of Appeal has been filed and counsel appointed - Def confirms she still wishes to go forward with the appeal.  Atty Lennon moves for stay of this sentence on advice of her appellate counsel.  Court respectfully declines to grant any stay.  Not appropriate to grant any stay pending appeal.  Records supplied for Court's review from Atty Lennon, are returned to his possession, not retained by the Court.
